context: The earliest examples of neoclassical architecture in Hungary may be found in <a0_0>Vác<a0_0/>. In this town <b4_0>the triumphal arch and the neoclassical façade of the baroque Cathedral<b4_0/> were designed by the French architect <a1_0><b5_0>Isidor Marcellus Amandus Ganneval<b5_0/><a1_0/> (Isidore Canevale) in the 1760s. Also the work of a French architect <a2_0>Charles Moreau<a2_0/> is the garden façade of the Esterházy Palace (1797–1805) in Kismarton (today Eisenstadt in Austria). The two principal architect of <b6_0>Neoclassicism<b6_0/> in Hungary was Mihály Pollack and <a3_0>József Hild<a3_0/>. Pollack's major work is the Hungarian National Museum (1837–1844).
